P. 136, l. 21. vel ciuis etiam. Madox’s conjecture ciuis is ren- dered certain by the repetition of the phrase in the question of the scholar immediately following. Clericus is a tempting conjecture in both cases,· but probably the sentence is intended to exhaust all the lay class; and ‘vel ciuis etiam ' only points to the fact that usury in a citizen might be thought a venial offence.

P. 137, l. 21. priuilegium demeretur. Cf. Gratian's Decretum II. c. 14. qu. 4 for a similar statement.
